# orcast prose gate

When writing or editing user-facing copy (web pages, components, default and
sample text, API messages, template replies, gate and glossary labels) or
audience-facing documents (whitepapers, demo scripts, voiceover narration, the
presentation deck, devpost copy, outreach), follow `.cca/PROSE_GATE_RULES.md`.

## Hard rules (do not emit)

- No em dash or en dash as ornament: `—`, `–`, `--`. Use a period or a comma, or
  restructure. Never substitute a colon or parentheses.
- No semicolons. Split into sentences or use "and".
- No colons in headers, titles, or inline, and no decorative `Label: body` colons
  in prose. Allowed only where strictly required by machine format (clock times,
  URLs, code, JSON or config key-values).
- No parentheses in running prose, headings, subheads, or table cells. Use "such
  as", "including", "for example", or separate sentences.
- No arrows `→`, `=>`, `-->`. Use "leads to", "then", or "so that".
- First-person singular only. No "we", "our", "us", or team framing.
- No smug narrative devices or double-dash (filler, synthetic contrast, false
  authority). No meta-framing ("In this section we", "We propose"). No passive
  results voice. No hedging "might", "could", "seems". No bullet lists inside
  body prose.
- No forbidden claims (see `.cca/CLAIM_BOUNDARIES.md`).

## Flag for review

- `, and` Oxford comma. Keep only where a list genuinely needs it.

## Exceptions

Markdown, LaTeX, and code syntax; machine-required colons (times, URLs, code,
config key-values); hyphens in established compounds; file paths in operator-only
text; scientific-paper citation and abbreviation style inside whitepaper `.tex`.

## Out of scope

Code comments and docstrings, and LLM system-prompt instruction text.
